\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {H$^+$ oscillations phase-lock to oscillatory holes, mediating electron-hole recombination.} (\textbf  {A}) Oscillatory hole formation rate over 5 seconds showing cardiac modulation (2.3 Hz, red envelope) with superimposed neural alpha (10 Hz) and gamma (40 Hz) components. Peak formation rate 1.5 $\times $ 10$^6$ holes/s occurs at cardiac systole. (\textbf  {B}) H$^+$ concentration ([H$^+$], nM) phase-locked to cardiac cycle, oscillating 30-50 nM around baseline pH 7.4 (gray dashed line). Peaks coincide with hole formation maxima. (\textbf  {C}) Oscillatory hole density accumulation from 0 to 5 $\times $ 10$^6$ holes/cell over 5 seconds, stabilized by H$^+$-electron coupling. Linear growth indicates sustained hole formation exceeds recombination. (\textbf  {D}) Electron pool availability decreasing from 1.000 to 1.005 $\times $ 10$^9$ e$^{-}$/cell as electrons are consumed by hole stabilization, confirming electron-hole recombination. (\textbf  {E}) Phase-locking analysis: normalized H$^+$ oscillations (blue) track hole density (purple) with correlation value 0.733, demonstrating tight coupling. (\textbf  {F}) Phase space trajectory showing H$^+$ concentration (40.0-43.0 nM) vs hole density (0-5 $\times $ 10$^6$) colored by time (purple to yellow, 0-5 s), revealing deterministic coupling dynamics. (\textbf  {G}) Electron-hole recombination rate increasing exponentially from 0.0 to 1.5 stabilization events/s, mediated by H$^+$ as electron donor. (\textbf  {H}) Frequency spectrum of hole oscillations showing peaks at cardiac (2.3 Hz, red), alpha (10 Hz, orange), and gamma (40 Hz, purple) frequencies. (\textbf  {I}) Frequency spectrum of H$^+$ oscillations showing dominant cardiac peak (2.3 Hz, red) and respiratory component (0.3 Hz, green), confirming physiological coupling. (\textbf  {J}) Cross-correlation between holes and H$^+$ peaking at 0.0 ms lag (red marker), proving instantaneous phase-locking. Correlation coefficient 0.8-1.0 indicates strong coupling. Mechanism demonstrates H$^+$ acts as electron shuttle stabilizing oscillatory holes through phase-locked recombination, providing physical substrate for categorical completion.}}{11}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:hole_mechanism}{{2}{11}{\textbf {H$^+$ oscillations phase-lock to oscillatory holes, mediating electron-hole recombination.} (\textbf {A}) Oscillatory hole formation rate over 5 seconds showing cardiac modulation (2.3 Hz, red envelope) with superimposed neural alpha (10 Hz) and gamma (40 Hz) components. Peak formation rate 1.5 $\times $ 10$^6$ holes/s occurs at cardiac systole. (\textbf {B}) H$^+$ concentration ([H$^+$], nM) phase-locked to cardiac cycle, oscillating 30-50 nM around baseline pH 7.4 (gray dashed line). Peaks coincide with hole formation maxima. (\textbf {C}) Oscillatory hole density accumulation from 0 to 5 $\times $ 10$^6$ holes/cell over 5 seconds, stabilized by H$^+$-electron coupling. Linear growth indicates sustained hole formation exceeds recombination. (\textbf {D}) Electron pool availability decreasing from 1.000 to 1.005 $\times $ 10$^9$ e$^{-}$/cell as electrons are consumed by hole stabilization, confirming electron-hole recombination. (\textbf {E}) Phase-locking analysis: normalized H$^+$ oscillations (blue) track hole density (purple) with correlation value 0.733, demonstrating tight coupling. (\textbf {F}) Phase space trajectory showing H$^+$ concentration (40.0-43.0 nM) vs hole density (0-5 $\times $ 10$^6$) colored by time (purple to yellow, 0-5 s), revealing deterministic coupling dynamics. (\textbf {G}) Electron-hole recombination rate increasing exponentially from 0.0 to 1.5 stabilization events/s, mediated by H$^+$ as electron donor. (\textbf {H}) Frequency spectrum of hole oscillations showing peaks at cardiac (2.3 Hz, red), alpha (10 Hz, orange), and gamma (40 Hz, purple) frequencies. (\textbf {I}) Frequency spectrum of H$^+$ oscillations showing dominant cardiac peak (2.3 Hz, red) and respiratory component (0.3 Hz, green), confirming physiological coupling. (\textbf {J}) Cross-correlation between holes and H$^+$ peaking at 0.0 ms lag (red marker), proving instantaneous phase-locking. Correlation coefficient 0.8-1.0 indicates strong coupling. Mechanism demonstrates H$^+$ acts as electron shuttle stabilizing oscillatory holes through phase-locked recombination, providing physical substrate for categorical completion}{figure.2}{}}
\newlabel{fig:hole_mechanism@cref}{{[figure][2][]2}{[1][10][]11}}
