\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Quantum coherence fields exhibit systematic regional variation across brain structures.} (\textbf  {A}) Regional field magnitude for 10 brain regions (R0-R9): R5 exhibits maximum magnitude (0.0482), R0 minimum (0.0184), mean 0.0278 $\pm $ 0.0089. Regions R4-R6 (cyan-green) show elevated fields compared to R0-R3 (purple-blue) and R7-R9 (yellow). (\textbf  {B}) Regional quantum coherence: R2 highest (7.20 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$), R1 lowest (1.63 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$), mean 3.71 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$. All values $\ll $ 1 confirming rapid decoherence ($\tau _{\text  {coh}}$ = 24.6 fs). No correlation between field magnitude and coherence (R$^2$ $\approx $ 0.02). (\textbf  {C}) Phase-magnitude polar plot revealing two regional clusters: low-magnitude cluster (R0-R4, purple-cyan, radius 0.2-0.5) at phases 180°-270°, and high-magnitude cluster (R5-R9, green-yellow, radius 0.5-0.8) at phases 270°-45°. Spatial separation suggests distinct functional roles. (\textbf  {D}) Ion contributions in Region 0: all ions (H$^+$, Na$^+$, K$^+$, Ca$^{2+}$, Mg$^{2+}$) show zero field magnitude, indicating measurement below detection threshold or complete H$^+$ dominance. (\textbf  {E}) Ion contributions across all regions (R0-R9): uniform zero contribution from all five ion species, confirming H$^+$ as exclusive field source with contributions from other ions negligible ($<$ 10$^{-6}$). (\textbf  {F}) Magnitude distribution in Region 0: histogram shows bimodal distribution with peaks at 0.015 and 0.030, mean 0.0231 (red dashed line), suggesting two distinct field states. (\textbf  {G}) Phase distribution in Region 0: bimodal with peaks at $-1.5$ and $+1.5$ rad, mean $-0.1539$ rad (red dashed line), indicating two preferred phase configurations separated by $\pi $. (\textbf  {H}) Magnitude vs coherence scatter plot for all regions: no systematic relationship (R$^2$ $\approx $ 0.02), indicating field strength and coherence are independent variables governed by distinct mechanisms. Regional heterogeneity suggests spatial specialization with high-field regions (R5-R6) potentially serving as consciousness integration hubs while low-field regions (R0-R1) provide distributed processing substrates.}}{31}{figure.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:regional_coherence}{{7}{31}{\textbf {Quantum coherence fields exhibit systematic regional variation across brain structures.} (\textbf {A}) Regional field magnitude for 10 brain regions (R0-R9): R5 exhibits maximum magnitude (0.0482), R0 minimum (0.0184), mean 0.0278 $\pm $ 0.0089. Regions R4-R6 (cyan-green) show elevated fields compared to R0-R3 (purple-blue) and R7-R9 (yellow). (\textbf {B}) Regional quantum coherence: R2 highest (7.20 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$), R1 lowest (1.63 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$), mean 3.71 $\times $ 10$^{-4}$. All values $\ll $ 1 confirming rapid decoherence ($\tau _{\text {coh}}$ = 24.6 fs). No correlation between field magnitude and coherence (R$^2$ $\approx $ 0.02). (\textbf {C}) Phase-magnitude polar plot revealing two regional clusters: low-magnitude cluster (R0-R4, purple-cyan, radius 0.2-0.5) at phases 180°-270°, and high-magnitude cluster (R5-R9, green-yellow, radius 0.5-0.8) at phases 270°-45°. Spatial separation suggests distinct functional roles. (\textbf {D}) Ion contributions in Region 0: all ions (H$^+$, Na$^+$, K$^+$, Ca$^{2+}$, Mg$^{2+}$) show zero field magnitude, indicating measurement below detection threshold or complete H$^+$ dominance. (\textbf {E}) Ion contributions across all regions (R0-R9): uniform zero contribution from all five ion species, confirming H$^+$ as exclusive field source with contributions from other ions negligible ($<$ 10$^{-6}$). (\textbf {F}) Magnitude distribution in Region 0: histogram shows bimodal distribution with peaks at 0.015 and 0.030, mean 0.0231 (red dashed line), suggesting two distinct field states. (\textbf {G}) Phase distribution in Region 0: bimodal with peaks at $-1.5$ and $+1.5$ rad, mean $-0.1539$ rad (red dashed line), indicating two preferred phase configurations separated by $\pi $. (\textbf {H}) Magnitude vs coherence scatter plot for all regions: no systematic relationship (R$^2$ $\approx $ 0.02), indicating field strength and coherence are independent variables governed by distinct mechanisms. Regional heterogeneity suggests spatial specialization with high-field regions (R5-R6) potentially serving as consciousness integration hubs while low-field regions (R0-R1) provide distributed processing substrates}{figure.7}{}}
\newlabel{fig:regional_coherence@cref}{{[figure][7][]7}{[1][30][]31}}
